<br>
==============================================<br>
Comparative Analysis of All Classes, All Realms (Vol. I) <br>
<br>
This Analysis seeks out to compare the differences in spells and abilities between class equivalents across realms and in relation to their standing in the realm as a whole. Not included are any issues outside of class balance, such as frontier mob aggression, dungeon itemization, and hunting ground availability. <br>
<br>
I will only give brief solutions to classes if any to balance them. Mostly it will consist of pointing out the actual imbalances and letting the presentation of information speak for itself. Everything is presented in a readily accessible format that solutions should almost be readily visible from the raw comparisons alone. This way, it also serves as a resource for everyone to quickly cross-index class information and the tools to make sound coherent arguments with a point of reference that everyone can have access to now. <br>
<br>
For most classes, I will compare racial ability scores along with access to equipment types and the abilities granted to that class. <br>
<br>
For spellcasting classes, I am also going to include the full list of secondary and specialization spell lines that they have access to, along with numbers that calculate all the secondary spells a class gets and the average number of specialization spells they get if they chose a random discipline. <br>
<br>
At the end of each section, I will rate the class overall with a score that both represents the balance it has with each other and balance as a contributing member of that realm. At the very end of this post is an Average score for each realm. <br>
<br>
I’ll start off with an easy example that is well balanced so I can set the tone about how each set of analyses are tabulated: <br>
<br>
<br>
*** ARMSMAN, WARRIOR, HERO *** <br>
<br>
ARMSMAN: Protect III, Intercept, Parry <br>
WARRIOR: Protect III, Evade I, Parry <br>
HERO: Protect III, Intercept, Parry, Evade I <br>
<br>
ARMSMAN: Plate Mail, Polearms, Large Shield, Crossbow <br>
WARRIOR: Chain Mail, 2h/1h, Large Shield, Thrown Weapon <br>
HERO: Scale Mail, Celtic Spear, Large Shield, Short Bow <br>
<br>
Armsman have both the best armor and the most singularly damaging weapon (but also the slowest). Highlanders are slightly optimized for melee so Albion ranks second in race selection. They lack any Evasion skills however. <br>
<br>
Warriors have access to the second best armor. Their weapon skills work differently, in that specializing in a specific weapon type grants both 1-handed and 2-handed use, granting flexibility in melee options. Most Midgard races are specialized for Melee. The only small drawback is lack of Intercept skill. <br>
<br>
Heroes also have the second best armor. They can use Celtic Spear which works like Polearm in a realm equivalent respect. None of Hibernia’s races are optimized for Melee, with the closest being the giant race Firebolgs have 10 points diverted towards empathy. Heroes do not lack any Evade I or Intercept skill. <br>
<br>
These classes were very straightforward and easy to analyze. Warriors are the strongest of these classes, with Armsman slightly underneath, and the Hero in last. At the each section includes a score. The scoring system does not analyze raw ability of each class as you might expect. If I were to take into account natural racial ability scores without regards to balance between realms, then Warriors would have 4.5 points, Armsman 4, and Heroes a 3.5. <br>
<br>
But, my scoring system takes into account that Midgard is designed to have the best races and weapon system for melee, Albion has the best armor and balance of melee/magic, and Hibernia is centered around magic specialization. Therefore, in relation to each other and with respect to what is expected of them in their realm, they are all perfectly balanced: <br>
<br>
Scores: <br>
ARMSMAN: 4 <br>
WARRIOR: 4 <br>
HERO: 4 <br>
<br>
<br>
*** PALADIN, THANE, CHAMPION *** <br>
<br>
PALADIN: Protect III, Parry, Intercept <br>
THANE: Protect II, Parry, Intercept <br>
CHAMPION: Protect II, Parry, Intercept <br>
<br>
PALADIN: Plate Mail, Large Shield <br>
THANE: Chain Mail, Medium Shield <br>
CHAMPION: Scale Mail, Medium Shield <br>
<br>
Paladin Chants: <br>
Secondary Spells: 0 <br>
Specializaiton Mean: 5 <br>
Self AF buff, Group Heal 6.5 seconds, Group Add Damage, Group AF buff, Resurrection I <br>
<br>
Thane Stormcalling: <br>
Secondary Spells: 0 <br>
Specialization Mean: 6 <br>
Direct Damage, Instant Direct Damage, Self STR buff, Self Add Damage, Point Blank AE Damage, AE Damage Line <br>
<br>
Champion Valor: <br>
Secondary Spells: 0 <br>
Specialization Mean: 5 <br>
Direct Damage, STR debuff, DEX debuff, Slowness debuff, Snare <br>
<br>
Nonmagic abilities are almost the same across classes. Paladins have the superior equipment advantage, while Thanes have their natural better selection of melee races and melee 1h/2h weapon options, while Champions have no nonmagical benefits compared to the other realms (which is expected). <br>
<br>
As far as Magic goes, the Thane is downright devastating and has a powerful arsenal of Direct Damage and AE spells to chain with. The Paladin is more of a Tankish defender with a strong group support role and helpful group chants. Both classes can opt to solo orange cons at risk. <br>
<br>
The Champion hails from the most magical Realm, but has the least amount of magic. In addition, the multi debuff nature of the spells were nerfed after it was thought they were too strong and the Champion was easily soloing Oranges. It was found that the DEX component of the debuff was actually a bug that made it 10x more powerful, so that was fixed and Champions were doubly nerfed from something that was in the first place a bug. Soloing Oranges now is out of the question. <br>
<br>
The Paladin is balancing in every respect to the other classes and as a member of its realm, by not having the most powerful spells, yet have the best equipment (Plate and Large Shield). The Champion is expected to have the worst nonmagical components to this class in relation to the other realms. If it did have the strongest magic like it was suppose to, then it would get a balanced score of 4. However, because it does not have the strongest magic out of its partner class and it has the weakest magic of all of them, they get a score of 3. <br>
<br>
The Thane is both the best in Melee attack and Damage output in every respect, with the largest arsenal of spells for being the “Melee strong at the cost of Magic” realm. The Thane is not unbalancing, but would revert to a score of 4 only after the Champion has superior spell capacity, so swings by the nerf bat are not necessary. <br>
<br>
PALADIN: 4 <br>
THANE: 4.5 <br>
CHAMPION: 3 <br>
<br>
<br>
*** MERCENARY, BERSERKER, BLADEMASTER *** <br>
<br>
MERCENARY: Protect III, Parry, Evade I, Intercept <br>
BERSERKER: Protect I, Parry, Evade III, Berserk IV <br>
BLADEMASTER: Protect III, Parry, Evade II, Intercept <br>
<br>
MERCENARY: Chain Mail, Medium Shield, Short Bow <br>
BERSERKER: Studded Leather, Small Shield <br>
BLADEMASTER: Reinforced Leather, Medium Shield, Short Bow <br>
<br>
Equipment-wise, Mercenaries of Albion are the best armed, with Blademaster in second and the Berserker in last. However the Berserker has the best Evade, with Blademaster in second, and Mercenary in last. They are overall balanced to each other in this respect. <br>
<br>
Berserkers are the only member of this class to have any special combat ability. They can increase their damage output for a while at the cost of their stamina. I do not have first hand experiences and this isn’t based on the raw comparisons, but I’ve heard that Thanes and Warriors still out damage Berserkers using that ability. <br>
<br>
Mercenaries and Blademasters have no special melee attack form whatsoever, and logs have been recorded where their melee/spellcasting tank outdamage them in pure melee by at least 30%. <br>
<br>
These classes are almost balanced with respect to each other, with Berserkers slightly ahead with the Berserk ability. However, none of them are balanced with respect to what their role is suppose to be in relation to their Realm, which can be summed up as a nonmagical high damage output tank with medium defense. The scores are lowered to reflect that: <br>
<br>
MERCENARY: 2 <br>
BERSERKER: 2.5 <br>
BLADEMASTER: 2 <br>
<br>
<br>
