All of these healing classes are well equipped in general, with Albion winning slightly with a better shield. Clerics get the most secondary spells, and rank second in amount of average specialization spells acquired. The Healer ranks second in secondary spells, and gets the most benefit through specialization. Odd to note, the Druid who hails from the magical realm gets the least amount of secondary spells and the least benefit through specialization. <br>
<br>
Through specialization, Clerics and Healers can become masters of crowd control. The buffing specialization is almost useless for any of these classes. The Druid does not have any form of crowd control, but because it can spend specialization points for a pet, it grants them the option of soloing oranges, which is a cruel joke on Hibernia. Instead of focusing on Healing, many druids spend points on their pet and prefer to solo oranges, and have weaker RVR healing abilities. Hibernia groups are often dependent on Hibernia’s range of secondary healers (Warden, Bard, Mentalist) and Druids are always a welcome sight in any group. <br>
<br>
Clerics have two excellent options. They get the best healing line of spells which includes group healing. They have great spell selection through Smite that is on par with spellcasters, including Stun and Mesmerize. They get a half a point bonus in score because they have more spells and their spells are more powerful than the Druids in multiple respects. Healers have the best pacification ability with mez, instant mez, stun, instant stun, and AE mez (overkill?). Pretty powerful coming from the melee strong realm, so the final score reflects that. Druids get the shaft in magic and their score reflects that they come from the Magic realm but currently are the weakest in magic of these classes, but they get a small half a point bonus for having a pet that lets them solo. <br>
<br>
