Friars get Leather armor and Evade IV and can specialize in Staves and Parry. However, with 1.0x specialization points, they have to choose to spend most of their points in their relatively underpowered Buff or Healing specialization, or to take up Staves and Parry with only 1.0x points. A Friar that chooses to specialize in a spell might as well had rolled a Cleric and get superior spells. If the Friar should be compared to any class for balancing purposes, they should be compared to the Warden and get 1.5x points. At most, they are a weak fighter with secondary spell abilities and buffs. <br>
<br>
Sorcerers are the only class in this selection that cannot directly heal life without draining it, but have many similarities to the classes of the other realms in many respects. They get 9 secondary spells through leveling and would work well at crowd control, if it wasn’t for the way spells are resisted currently. Crowd Control works best when grouped and fighting grouped mobs, often they are higher level. All casters face this issue, even the Clerics and Healers of the previous section, however half of their job is also to heal, sorcerer primarily casts on monsters. <br>
<br>
Shamans get 9 secondary spells, however their specialization spells are some of the worst to select from. They do get access to regeneration spells through their healing specialization. Their other specializations aren’t plentiful enough in spell selection to make them worthwhile. <br>
<br>
Weaker than Sorcerers, yet hailing from the Magical Realm, Mentalist only get access to 6 secondary spells and are tied in the worst access to specialization spells. To top that off are the reports that some of the spells that Mentalists like Short Term Charm Humanoid and Paralyze are broken. They are one of the least played classes of Hibernia. <br>
<br>
Friars watered down healing spells and combat potential reminds me of Hibernia’s Warden who gets 1.5x specialization and fills its role nicely there. Until then, Frairs remain underpowered and are not able to fully support their realm. Sorcerers are better off than Mentalist in a few respects, but fall short of being a vital realm member. Shamans are best off specializing in Healing for Regeneration abilities, but even then they are not that enhancing and are short term. The other Spell lines to specialize in are terrible, the secondary spells are the best choice. The Mentalist is broken, smallest spell selection, and has broken spells, yet comes from Hibernia, giving it the lowest score possible. All these classes need to be reworked. <br>
<br>
FRIAR: 2.5 <br>
SORCERER: 2 <br>
SHAMAN: 2.5 <br>
MENTALIST: 1 <br>
<br>
<br>
*** WIZARD, RUNEMASTER, ELDRITCH *** <br>
<br>
WIZARD: Cloth, Quickcast <br>
RUNEMASTER: Cloth, Quickcast <br>
ELDRITCH: Cloth, Quickcast <br>
<br>
Wizard Path of Earth, Ice, Fire: <br>
Secondary Spells: 6 <br>
Specialization Mean: 2.33 <br>
(Secondary) Self AF buff, Add Damage, Direct Damage, Stop Movement, Bolt Direct Damage, Direct Damage <br>
(Earth) Damage Shield, Bolt Direct Damage <br>
(Ice) Direct Damage and Snare, Direct Damage and Ice Resist debuff, AE Damage <br>
(Fire) Direct Damage, AE Damage <br>
<br>
Runemaster Darkness, Suppression, Runecarving: <br>
Secondary Spells: 8 <br>
Specialization Mean: 2.66 <br>
(Secondary) Direct Damage, DEX debuff, STR debuff, AF buff, Stop Movement, Bolt Direct Damage, Group Enhance Speed Movement, Direct Damage <br>
(Darkness) Direct Damage, Direct Damage with Darkness debuff, Add Damage <br>
(Suppression) Absorb Shield, Direct Damage and Snare, Confusion <br>
(Runecarving) Bolt Direct Damage, AE Damage <br>
<br>
Eldritch Way of Moon, Sun, Eclipse: <br>
Secondary Spells: 6 <br>
Specialization Mean: 3 <br>
(Secondary) Self AF buff, Self Damage Shield, Direct Damage, Stun, Bolt Direct Damage, Direct Damage <br>
(Moon) Direct Damage and Snare, Point Blank AE Damage, STR/CON debuff, Disease <br>
(Sun) Direct Damage, DEX/QUI debuff, AE Mesmerize <br>
(Eclipse) Bolt Direct Damage, AE Damage <br>
<br>
All these classes face the same spell resist issues that plague all spellcasters against slightly higher level mobs. The difference is that almost all of these caster spells are cast on monsters and not allies. Also, despite specialization, the damage benefits through specialization is minimal and the selection is small for the most part. <br>
<br>
Wizards get a small but fair access to secondary spells, with very little benefits through specialization. They do have the benefit of having the most Intelligent race, Avalonians, and they do not need to be the magically strongest since they hail from Albion. They get a 2. <br>
<br>
Runemasters have a host of Secondary spells to choose from, and more variety in spell selection (even a group enhance speed) and better spells through specialization (Like the Single Damage Absorb Shield). Runemasters are superior in every respect to Wizards and Eldritchs, even having higher damage spells that cost less mana, all this coming from the least Magical specialized realm. For that reason, Runemasters get a bonus point, but also get deducted for having the same resist issues that all casters face. No Nerf bat needs to be swung, but rather the other classes need serious revamping a notch above the Runemaster. Until the classes are revamped, Runemaster stays slightly above the balance standard with a score of 4.5. <br>
<br>
Eldritches, where do I begin? They have the same small and poor selection of spells as do Wizards, specialization doesn’t mean much, the Elf is the second strongest spellcaster race, and all this coming from Hibernia and what is suppose to be the most damaging spellcaster class in all of Camelot. Fix me? <br>
<br>
WIZARD: 2 <br>
RUNEMASTER: 4.5 <br>
ELDRITCH: 1 <br>
